    "created_at": "2015-08-07T05:09:59Z",
    "updated_at": "2015-08-07T05:21:53Z",
    "body": "I think I have found out the root cause:\n\n`blink` performs microtask actions after reaching the microtask checkpoint, e.g. after executing a piece of JavaScript code, and during the checkpoint the Promise's callback will be called. Every time `blink` executes JavaScript the code will be guarded inside a `V8RecursionScope`, and by the time code runs beyond the scope `blink` will think we have reached a microtask checkpoint.\n\nHowever Electron ignores the whole `V8RecursionScope` thing when executing JavaScript, so in our example the callback passed to `setImmediate` is not guarded inside a `V8RecursionScope`, while the `document.createElement` call is. So when `document.createElement` ends `blink` thinks we have reached a microtask checkpoint, and calls the Promise's callback.\n\nThe fix is straightforward, we can simply wrap the code in `V8RecursionScope` when calling into libuv. But it needs to expose internal pieces of blink so it will take some time before I can verify whether the fix works.\n"
  },
